segments.text: This is Deborah Beale, and I am interviewing Dr. David Norton on the history of the Texas Engineering Experiment Station.
The date is June 12, 1984.
Are you ready to go ahead and start?
And I'd like to start with just a little background.
Let's start with your education and how you came to come here.
OK. Let's see.
You want to start at the college level of education?
I came to A&M in 1958.
as a student in mechanical engineering and did an ME, a bachelor of science, and then a master's of science.
I graduated in 63 and then went to Purdue and did a PhD in mechanical engineering and specialized in propulsion.
Then, having been commissioned here, I was then ready for active duty.
So I did active duty in the Ordnance Corps and was eventually assigned to the Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena, California on my tour of active duty after an officer's basic in the East Coast.
Then I was out there two years.
And then in January of 1970, I took an appointment here as an assistant professor in the aerospace engineering department.
So I stayed in that capacity until January of 1982, basically.
And which time I came over here and began as an assistant director for what was then called program.
and am now the assistant director of research.
When did you first become aware of Tunis?
Probably my second day here.
As a student or as a... No, not really as a student at all.
Even my graduate research days in the early 60s, late 50s,
TEAS, as you'll be finding out, was not as pervasive an influence as it is today in engineering research.

For example, the mechanical engineering department really didn't interface a great deal with engineering department section, although a few faculty had done work through them and with them during the war and after.
They operated the mechanical engineering department separately and worked out assistantships and fellowships separately and didn't really have much of a research program.
As a matter of fact, the reason many of the colleges didn't have a real research program were only doing a very nominal amount of graduate work.
and the need for funded research was not as large as it is today.
So, it just really wasn't that pervasive of a factor.
What was your first project through TEAS?
Well, the excitement that brought me here, as opposed to the other places I was looking at, was the Space Shuttle.
Professor Al Kronk, who was the department head at that time,
in the interview process indicated to me that he had been asked by Johnson Spacecraft Center to develop capability in dealing with shuttle problems.
And specifically, they had problems with propulsion, which was my specialty.
So the offer to get involved and begin to do research on space shuttles

was my inducement to come here because that was a major new exciting program that had all the disciplines that I was interested in going with it and it was yet had an applied side that was appealing to me that I'd be able to see this thing designed, developed, flown over the years.
So that's the reason I came and that's the first research project.
It was, I was under contract in NASA basically continuously for the next 12 years on this mission.
I don't know if this is directly related to the propulsion, but the wind tunnel was used for that.
Do you know what it was used for immediately before that?
Before that major relationship was established between JSC and our air department, I think it was used to store hay.
There was a period of time where it was basically unused or used sporadically at best in the 60s.
As far as I could tell,
It was basically unused for a period of time until the late 60s.
In 69, it took some aid of NASA, old equipment, old recorder, old stuff, and some people that were sent up here to help us get modernized from JSC, a guy named Ray Moore.
We had a lot of help from them in trying to get us developed as a facility where they could come

do some testing and some evaluation that they would otherwise have to go to one of the major NASA centers, Langley or Ames, or hire down at one of the contractors, where they wouldn't really be a party to the work.
So they could actually come in the lab and turn their roller shirt sleeves up, get in there and feel what was going on in a friendly, cooperative environment.
And that's what they were looking for to establish here, and they did.
change from director of programs to director of research.
Was that a real change in the jobs?
No, it was not.
It was a change or a different recognition, I think, in that the research, the purpose of engineering firm station is research.
It's not business.
It's not research.
And this, in essence, made it clear that this was, I was interested in a research position that led to, you know, the main heartbeat.
I wasn't a peripheral
I wasn't in anything else but Missouri.
What is your job now?
What do you do?
My job and most of the jobs I already have is what I want it to be, basically.
What I want it to be is developing the research potential of TEAS and Texas A&M for the benefit of the state.
I'm very clear about that role.
In my opinion, the role is to make the infrastructure, the technical infrastructure of Texas be as strong as possible.
And at the same time, to develop that in the sense of
research capability and technical manpower.

The technical manpower we developed basically by providing assistance to graduate students through work, not through gifts, through work and assistantship and buying millions of dollars of equipment that is used for research but also is used to teach at the graduate and senior level of the undergraduate program.
So in that way we developed the capabilities and the technical manpower pool.
And we also take all this intellect that's here and make it, otherwise it's not available, make it available to the benefit of the state.
To do that, you have to have a large enough pool that you have a group that can do almost anything.
And when the state has a need, you are simply the conduit into that pool to apply it.
And then when that need goes away, you tap into another part of the pool for another problem.

You have to have this pool, and that takes a lot of work and support to keep that pool of 400 or 500 engineers going here, keep them bubbling up and exciting the students and developing their capabilities so that they're available.
If you only had 100, you wouldn't be able to serve that role.
You wouldn't be able to say, whatever the problem is, we have the talent.
It takes this level of a group to keep the process going.
How did you first get involved in administration of TEAS?
Skip Porter called me.
He said, I want you to be assistant director.
I told him no twice.
Finally, I told him yes.
We started out on a half-time basis, a three-quarter time basis, and finally a full-time basis.
Because I had other things that I was doing in Arrow.
I was now a full professor over there, traveling internationally in my own research.
I developed an environmental aerodynamics laboratory, and we were starting to do three, four hundred thousand dollars worth of research, and junior faculty and graduate students.
Things were really bubbling over there.
It was for some reluctance that I consider that, because I'm by no stretch of imagination, at least initially configured for administrative work.
My strengths have always been the technical, personal sort of commitment, as opposed to getting other people to do things, but you can learn some of the skills.
When did you get the environmental aerodynamics portion?
No, it wasn't before.
Environmental aerodynamics later.

OK. OK, at this point, someplace around in the mid, another element of the story, my personal story, is about the mid-'70s, the enrollment of aerospace engineering, as an example, went from 100, say, like 200 freshmen in the fall of 72 to like 60 freshmen in the fall of 73.
So there was a precipitous step function in enrollment.

And in order to maintain the faculty, there were about nine or 10 at that time, active full-time faculty, it was clear that we were going to have to diversify and go heavily into research instead of being quarter-time research, be pre-quarter-time research.
And those of us that looked around and said, well, where is the money?
Where are we going to do that?
We all did our own thing individually
sought out other areas, or broaden their own areas.
And one of the things I looked at was something called environmental aerodynamics, which is not propulsion.
It is the flow of wind and its effect on man, buildings, and the sea, and offshore platforms, things like that.
And at that time, that was something that was
being developed nationwide.
I went to Colorado State for eight weeks to where the United States' most prestigious guy is named Cermak.
I spent eight weeks with him learning this branch of engineering.
I brought that back here and over the next several years developed that as an area of study.
I developed two courses, graduate courses and an area of research.
So I did a great deal of that, in addition to whatever little bits of NASA work that was still to be done.
Was this the group that was involved in the oil, or were you involved in the oil spill research?
No.
Well, yes, I have been involved in oil spill research, but not from the point of view of Roy Hand, who goes out when there's an oil spill and goes out and tries to
analyze the situation and stuff like that.
My involvement has been in terms of the fluid mechanics of how you skim it off the water.
Well, that's the research that was done in the mid-'70s, right?
Mm-hmm, right.
And it developed a training program for them?
Mm-hmm, eventually, yes, right.
Did that start with the beginning of that lab?
No, that lab was created, I think, about 1980.
No, we were just loosely associated with people around the campus that were doing
work in oil spill, and there was people in civil engineering, myself and Arrow and other people, and that was one of those opportunities that came along that I got involved with about two years.
Whose brainchild was that?
I don't know, it may go back to, I know Charlie Rodenberger was involved with a contract with the Department of Transportation.
And it involved the Coast Guard, in which they were trying to find mechanisms to contain oil spill to sea, especially when there were the current.
Because the booms that they had, the oil would just go unneeded, pile up against one side and get so deep and then go unneeded.
So they were looking for ways to combat that tendency.
And that's the kind of research that at least I was involved in.
In the early and mid-'70s with the energy crisis, did that change the direction of your research?
Not so much, except that one of the areas of research that I began to look at was generation of wind power by wind.
So I added that into the things that we were doing in my lectures and courses.
So I brought in that sense, but I didn't, I wasn't never just fundamentally in energy research.
Did money for that type of thing become more readily available at that point?
Uh, sure.
And many, many people around the campus, like in chemical engineering and other places, lacked on to that, and that concept didn't get involved in a great deal of research.
Everything from oil shales and all kinds of things.
But I never personally got involved, not too much.
But that was the time in which people began to do that, to get some of that Department of Energy money.
Did you find that with the late 70s, when the popularity of the space program went downhill, was it harder to get money for your research?
Sure.
That's the reason why I was still doing work for them.
It was not something that would be a full-time research activity, and so I needed to develop a parallel.
Is that the same reason they're dropping students?
Yeah, right.
So there wasn't that much teaching.
So... Not only did you have trouble getting money, but you didn't have the students as well?
That's right.
Okay.
So you really had... You know, there was... Nobody would fire you, but on the other hand, you had a sense to keep the team together.
And now we have...
Well, we now have the largest aerospace engineering department in the country.
We have something like 700 students, which is by far and away.
We were down to like 100 students total.
But we had the same teams there.
And they're there because when the time came, we knew what to do to keep ourselves there.
And so the role of playing back and forth between research and teaching and engineering, which is cyclical, is absolutely critical.
If you don't have that flexibility,
you're not going to make too many perturbations in this field.
The aerospace is coming back.
Oh, yeah.
It's here.
When did this new wave start?
Well, it really started like a year or two after the big low.
We've been plotting a curve.
It's been going like that ever since.
It's just been 10% per year or 20% per year, and it's just been going, going, going.
What do you think precipitated that?
Well, I think the next thing that
Historically, it was the space shuttle.
In 1969, we had landing on the moon, and we had the rest of the Apollo.
And the Apollo came, and that was, oh, we're on the moon again.
It just lost interest.
Then we had a gap there.
And meanwhile, in 1969, we started working on the shuttle.
And it did its first flights in the mid-1974 or 75, I guess.

so that was the next big big thing so about 75 the shuttle then they dropped tested it off the 747 and they did this they did that so that's uh begin to reawaken the american public a little bit but that and i think other things uh i think
reconsideration of what we would do in defense, which is, of course, a big implore of aerospace people.
Pretty good time as far as the airlines were concerned, and major programs to develop the 757 and the 767.
There was a number of little things that kept things parking alone.
Who do you deal with as an administrator inside the system, inside the teams?
That's the answer I'm getting from everybody.
No, primarily it would be TASE, N-T-A-M-U, and in some cases other universities in the system, Prairie View, and also other research entities that are in this stage around the nation.
How about outside the system?
Who do you usually meet with?
Well, we meet with the University of Texas at Arlington.

I mean, this year I probably had four or five meetings with the University of Texas at Austin in terms of the water research and other things that we're trying to coordinate, you know, the feeling of cooperation with UT.
Is that a new feeling?
What?
Is that a feeling of cooperation new?
Yeah, it was, you know, right, right, fairly new.
The last few years?
The last two years.
I think it's an impetus of the posture that the chancellors take.
Do you deal with them in the state or national legislature?
Yeah, we have the speaker of the house, Texas House here, and a couple of representatives.
So yeah, we deal with this.
We're a state agency.
A lot of things happen over here that don't necessarily go through the university, so people come here and see the research.
I know Jane Armstrong is the liaison.
Yeah, she is our primary liaison.
So are you the liaison with most of the other academic institutions?
Yes.
That would be right.
When it comes to research and engineering research, probably that would be more what I would be doing when it comes to legislature or other
Chamber of Commerce, other kinds of liaison that we want to build, Jane just generally is there.
But we don't have any written instructions on that.
How have changes in administration changed the way TEAS functions from your viewpoint?
Well, first place,
I came here when Fred Benson was in charge of most everything.
So there was no changes for a decade or so.
Between 1970 and 1978 or not, there were no changes.
Then we had our big new organization and things have been sort of in a turmoil in terms of that ever since.
That really has no effect in some senses, or it has all the effect.
It just depends how much you want to watch it.
I think we've been able to be as effective as we are because we've tried not to concentrate on it too much.
We have a little expression we use around here.
We like to just keep laying bricks.
Let everybody else worry about it, but we just want to put another brick down.

So that's really been what I've, while all those things have been happening, my feeling is that we just ought to continue to get opportunities to do research and continue to identify those who do the research and just keep our relationships at a high level.
The funding agency is keeping going.
Have there been any particular points in your memory, too, that have been some low points?
when this broke down or was threatened?
Well, I would say no.
It's been very general, very high plane of professional activity over here all the way through.
At least certainly my dealings with Skidport.
So I haven't had the feeling, maybe a little lately,
that we weren't able to take advantage of all the opportunities we could because things aren't settled in the administration.
But it's factors external that's really keeping who we see dead ends because you can't get decisions or people are in place.
You can't hire the people you want to because the apartment is not there, et cetera, et cetera.
So those kind of things, but not as far as us within TEAS.
We feel like that.
There's plenty of opportunities to take advantage of it if the rest of the people want to.
How much influence has the Research Foundation had on your work?
The Research Foundation, I have a long history with the Research Foundation.
I bet if you went over there you'd find that I've had more contracts with the Research Foundation than any researcher on campus.

As a researcher dealing with the Research Foundation, although there have been minor frustrations, I've always felt that they were trying to help the researcher and there were such good people out there.
What is not commonly understood by the faculty is that

Research Foundation is indeed not an entity of the Texas A&M University System and employs no professional research faculty and is indeed a place to make things easier by verging on the fact that it's not part of Texas A&M.
And I think if you would ask a typical new faculty member that he thinks he works for the Research Foundation and I think that they try
to make them, not directly, but indirectly.
And that causes some confusion as to who they report to, who's responsible for their political tenure, who are the people, indeed, that they should look to for their long-term support group.
So in that sense, it's confusing to find out.
And that's not a plus.
On the other side, there are times when they handle kind of details that really nobody wants to get involved with.
People want to take the time complying with OSHA and complying with all the federal regulations that apply to a contract and all the bookkeeping and such.
They provide a valuable service.
Were most of your contracts through them also involving teams?
Sure, because any research I did involved teams.
The contract would usually read, uh, the Research Foundation checks this contract and is named the Texas Engineering Experiment Station as the entity who will do the research.
And the Texas Engineering Experiment Station is named Dr. Norton as the principal investigator.
So every bit of research that I've ever done over the last 15 years has always been the engineering term extension.
Now, only in the last few years has it been possible to do contracts directly with the engineering term extension without the research foundation involved at all.
But I've always been a teaser for it.
I've always gotten two or three paychecks, different ones.
So, what is the difference between teams and researchers?
Well, the Research Foundation is a not-for-profit, arm's length corporation that was set up to circumvent purchasing regulations in the state of Texas.
for the purpose of doing, managing, in a fiscal sense, project accounting, which the university does not have.
They don't have a project accounting system.
So it was convenient for the university and everybody to invent this organization to do project accounting, to do purchasing, to do certain things like that.
And it has
No people except bookkeepers and lawyers.
So in this far, it is useful to use them.
And it's useful to use them.
Oh, the other third and fourth thing was the university doesn't have a means to retain overhead on federal contracts.
So they have no way of paying for the bookkeeping system.
But the Research Foundation can.
So they keep some of the overhead.
to do the bookkeeping.
The university wouldn't be able to because they had to give all the overhead back.
So it made sense then for them to create, or us to create, this bookkeeping outfit that could absorb a little of the overhead to pay for itself.
And then whatever was left over of the overhead, we shipped back to Austin.
And they put in the general revenue.
So it made sense in a couple of ways.
It doesn't necessarily make the same sense in your interpretation.
But we're here as a team, all our sister agencies, the TAs and the TTs, and the KTs and the TKFs.
And if that's the common will, then we'll be glad to participate.
But it's just something of convenience.
It has no real A&M significance.
It's not really a part of Texas A&M or Texas A&M.
So has TEAS established some kind of system?
Sure.
Always had to.
See, the Research Foundation does no state contracts.
Not allowed to.
So if you have a state contract with another agency, how do you do it?
Well, you have to have your own book.
We've always had it now.
And we always send federal contracts for them.
We always do the state contracts.
The industrial contracts, we do about 50-50 when we think it makes sense.
It doesn't require a lot of guaranteeing of this and that.
We do them through here, right through our own shop.
Good Lord, you got a shop.
And it works out fine.
When it's complicated and it needs something that they provide, then we send it over there.
That explains a lot that I hadn't understood.
And I don't think a lot of people understand.
No.
No.
Almost nobody understands it.
There were great changes in the 60s in terms of the building of the nuclear science center, the data processing center, and that type of thing.
Did you see a lot of changes in the types of research that were going on in the 60s or 70s?
Well, I wasn't here in the 60s, so I can't... No, in the 70s, I'm talking about.
Okay.
Any spurts of the same rapid change, you had the shuttle come in and... Yeah, well, that's just peculiar to my department.
What was happening in the 60s is the leadership of a few really brave guys.
We were...
establishing capabilities at A&M that led us to be able to really operate in the 70s.
Things like the Cyclotron, things like the NICU Science Center, things like, many things if you look around now and wonder where they got started, they got started here.
And I'm sure you've talked to Dr. Capoon and Mark Will and Fred Benson.
Those guys, and Rudder,
look for ways to progress and establish capabilities.
We built a building over here, the Space Research Center, the T building, NASA funds.
Things like that were happening and we took a lot of risks and built a lot of facilities.
Most of them worked out, some of them didn't.
That's what I look back and think I see there is without much research capability,
Before 1965, there really wasn't any research done here.
Not that there wasn't some good research done, but the volume was.
You could say that the research really didn't get started until then.
So people were putting into place facilities and capabilities and programs that a university that didn't have a lot of traditional research could grab a hold of and begin to have a reason to do this.
Those were very important steps in my mind, very far-reaching, brave steps to take.
So by the time you got here, the facility was already here?
There was a wind tunnel.
Even though it wasn't active, it was there.
There was a nuclear science center, and there was all these things here that had been constructed and built basically on
on the feeling that would be important.
Maybe they couldn't justify it all the way by the people that were here at the time.
And certainly, you can't justify building a wind tunnel when you don't have an aerospace engineering department.
But basically, that's what happened.
Gilchrist built that wind tunnel.
And everybody said, what a folly.
And it was a folly for a long time.
But it has also been a great source
visitors and research and all kinds of activities that have helped make the repetition of A&E.
What do you think that TEAS balances in terms of the testing services and the type of research?
It's often asked, and I think everybody that asks it is really looking to confirm what they really believe about TEAS.
First of all, you've got to understand that TEAS is really just about five or ten people up here.
Everybody else is out there in the department.
So when you say, what you're really asking is what do the faculty of Texas, of the College of Engineering and the other associated departments really do?
That's what you're really asking.
Through TEAS.
Through TEAS, right.
has $1.05 that they use to direct the program.
The other four-fifths comes from the blood, sweat, and tears of the individual faculty member who go to Washington and say, I'm good.
I'm going to do this research.
You're going to fund me.
And they take that proposal and send it around the country.
And all his competitors mark it up.
And if he wins the competition, he brings it back.
So teeth didn't tell him what to do.
He just did it, and we're the vehicle through which he does it.
So when you say tease research, what you're really saying is, what do the faculty members, what do College of Engineering do?
OK, now let's answer that question.
They do whatever their conscience dictates and whatever they perceive that the administration would reward.
There is an opportunity for those
who feel they make contributions to this state, they certainly can mark one.
If it involves some testing, that's fine.
Frankly, testing always is a lower order on the economic research chain because it's usually dollars received for dollars of actual value delivered.
If you do testing
You propose something, I'll do $100 worth of testing, and you have to do $100 worth of testing.
There isn't any fat.
It's just work.
Yeah.
It's just work.
So normally, a mature faculty member won't get involved in too much testing, because he doesn't have any way to pay for the graduate students that he wants to educate.
And how do graduate students get educated in engineering?
By the research contract that they bring in.
There is no other mechanism.
You're getting paid through some sort of assistantship, I guess, by the fact you're working.
That opportunity to do that work was provided by some faculty member having the opportunity to do some research.
That's the same way it works for all 300 or 400 engineering students.
People get contracts.
And they make the contract read in such a way that they can hire some graduate students.
That's how they get educated.
But that's the process.
And doing the testing doesn't add to that process.
So yes, there is testing.
And generally what happens is we have non-faculty people doing the testing because we would like to maintain a service level to the industry in Texas and keep that connection going.
That's our business.
But generally, that's occupied.
We have the engineering test lab.
Charlie Neely has done that for 30 years, and before him, 20 years, other people did it.
They test fans.
It's one of the two places in the United States where you can test a fan to certify that it meets certain standards.
That doesn't necessarily have a large educational value.
They do it at the annex, but the industry sure loved it.
They said, don't go away.
We need it.
So there's 100 or so industries that deal with Texas A&M.
Every year, they say, Texas A&M hangs a moon.
They do this work for us.
But it's a low-level activity.
It's self-supporting.
Self-supporting activity?
Fine.
It's not costly.
Yeah, right.
And a lot of goodwill.
And there's other activities.
About half of the work that's done in the wind tunnel is in that category.
And we have some graduate students, some co-ops, and Oren Nix, who's a non-faculty, but very dedicated, bright guy.
They do that work.
Fine.
The other half of the time,
It's research work from the faculty in the Department of Aero and ME, et cetera.
I don't know if I've diverged off the question, but that is indeed the way it's done.
So testing is done, but it's generally done by non-faculty people, because the faculty understands that there's no great glory in it, and there's no good way to get a lot of money in it.
I know the data processing center is now being separated.
Right, there's another example.
Why was that separated and other services not?
Okay, let me tell you how that worked.
When TEAS has certain funds, which are very small, as you know, compared to the
Our state budget compared to the system-wide budget is like 180.
We get 180 of the state funds.
But the funds that we get are fairly flexible.
They don't say, you have to do this piece of testing with it.
They just say, go make good research happen.
So we're in a position that occasionally,
risks can be taken with no detrimental effects in terms of reportability.
In 1958, when the question of who and how was going to take the risk on this computer craft, it was only the engineering experiment station that stood up and said, gee, maybe we can help.
So for the next 25 years, we helped.
The way we help, we will start something, but it has to pay for itself.
So we were doing a $6 million a year operation to pay for out of research, out of fees generated by the administrative side, out of fees generated by the university to pay for computing for students.
Of course, they weren't paying much.
They were paying like $200,000 a year out of a $6 million budget.
But the attitude of the faculty is always,
Just like your chalk is free when you go in the classroom, just like your paper is in the cupboard, computing ought to be free.
And we all know that's impossible.
But it is also very difficult for a faculty member to come up with hard cash to pay for his computer.
So basically what happens, when something gets to be successful to the point where a large number of faculty feel it is part of the daily conduct of their business, they want the university
take it over and make it free to them.
And that's what they did.
Now what the university might do to make it free to them is they take money from somebody else because they only got so much money.
They will maybe take part of your operating expenses away from your department or they'll take away from some other fund.
and it won't be there, and then they'll make it for you.
Somebody else over here, if they can figure it out, should realize he got robbed to make it free.
He's using it, too.
Well, of course, he's using it, too, but he got robbed more than he's using it.
Right.
Okay, so that's what generated it.
That's also what happened in the cyclotron.
The engineering experimentation started, got it going.
Physics got heavily involved when it thought it was neat, but didn't want to pay the fees.
So they say, university, take this over so it's free.
So they did.
So that's our job.
That's part of our job, is to introduce new technologies into the mainstream.
We keep going up trying to find things like that and try to make it successful.
And when it's successful, then the university would say, gee, we better have made this free.
They'd take it over, and we'd make something else.
It's a great process.
So it frees up your money.
Sure.
We don't want to operate those damn things.
They're a drain on us.
God, I didn't take constant management, constant problems.
I'd love to give that away.
Do you feel the focus of TEAS has changed at all since you started here?
Since I was a faculty member?
Yeah, I think it has somewhat.
I think there's been an increased recognition of the role that the engineering experiment station could play in the development of the state.
It wasn't so apparent in the 70s because we were just moving along at all.
The state economy was just on a roll.
But as the end of the 70s came along, the bloom was off the rose a little bit.
People began to ask, all right, when this oil money runs out, how have we spent that money to do anything lasting for the state?
And the next thing that came about was the realization that the industry of the future, the main currency of that industry is going to be knowledge as opposed to hard goods.
So if you take those two factors, and then the third factor is the largest investment the state makes is education.
By far, you see, what we need to do
